            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-mod5function">
        <p>
          We know <m>R_5 = \left\{ {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} \right\}</m> and <m>R_6 = \left\{ {0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} \right\}</m>.
          For each of the following functions,
          determine if the function is an injection and determine if the function is a surjection.
          Justify all conclusions.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f\x R_5 \to R_5</m> by <m>f( x ) = x^2 + 4 \pmod 5</m>,
                for all <m>x \in R_5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g\x R_6 \to R_6</m> by <m>g( x ) = x^2 + 4 \pmod 6</m>,
                for all <m>x \in R_6</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>F\x R_5 \to R_5</m> by <m>F( x ) = x^3 + 4 \pmod 5</m>,
                for all <m>x \in R_5</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-5">
        <p>
          For each of the following functions,
          determine if the function is an injection and determine if the function is a surjection.
          Justify all conclusions.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f\x\mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> defined by
                <m>f( x ) = 3x + 1</m>, for all <m>x \in \Z</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>F\x\mathbb{Q} \to \mathbb{Q}</m> defined by
                <m>F( x ) = 3x + 1</m>, for all <m>x \in \Q</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g\x\mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by
                <m>g( x ) = x^3</m>, for all <m>x \in \R</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>G \x\mathbb{Q} \to \mathbb{Q}</m> defined by
                <m>G( x ) = x^3</m>, for all <m>x \in \Q</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>k \x \R \to \R</m> defined by
                <m>k(x) = e^{-x^2}</m>, for all <m>x \in \R</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>K\x \R^* \to \R</m> defined by <m>K(x) = e^{-x^2}</m>,
                for all <m>x \in \R^*</m>.
                Note: <m>\R^* = \left\{ x \in \R \mid x \geq 0 \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>K_1 \x \R^* \to T</m> defined by <m>K_1(x) = e^{-x^2}</m>,
                for all <m>x \in \R^*</m>,
                where <m>T = \left\{ y \in \R \mid 0 \lt y \leq 1 \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>h \x\R \to \R</m> defined by
                <m>h ( x ) = \dfrac{2x}{x^2 + 4}</m>, for all <m>x \in \R</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>H \x \{x \in \R \mid x \geq 0 \} \to \left\{ y \in \R \left| 0 \leq y \leq \dfrac{1}{2} \right. \right\}</m> defined by <m>H ( x ) = \dfrac{2x}{x^2 + 4}</m>,
                for all <m>x \in \{x \in \R \mid x \geq 0 \}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_forexample">
        <p>
          For each of the following functions,
          determine if the function is a bijection.
          Justify all conclusions.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>F\x\mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}</m> defined by <m>F( x ) = 5x + 3</m>,
                for all <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>G\x\Z \to \Z</m> defined by
                <m>G( x ) = 5x + 3</m>, for all <m>x \in \Z</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f\x ( \R -\left\{ 4 \right\} ) \to \R</m> defined by <m>f ( x ) = \dfrac{3x}{x - 4}</m>,
                for all <m>x \in \left( \R - \{ 4 \} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>g\x ( \R -\left\{ 4 \right\} ) \to ( \R - \left\{ 3 \right\} )</m> defined by <m>g ( x ) = \dfrac{3x}{x - 4}</m>,
                for all \linebreak<m>x \in \left( \R - \{ 4 \} \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        \end{tabular}
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-sumdivisors">
        <p>
          Let <m>s\x\mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m>,
          where for each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
          <m>s( n )</m> is the sum of the distinct natural number divisors of <m>n</m>.
          This is the <em>sum of the divisors function</em>
    <idx><h>sum of divisors function</h></idx>
          that was introduced in <xref ref="PA_otherfunctions"></xref>
          from <xref ref="S_introfunctions"></xref>.
          Is <m>s</m> an injection?
          Is <m>s</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-numdivisors">
        <p>
          Let <m>d\x\mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m>,
          where <m>d( n )</m> is the number of natural number divisors of <m>n</m>.
          This is the <em>number of divisors function</em>
    <idx><h>number of divisors function</h></idx>
          introduced in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_numberofdivisors"/> from <xref ref="S_introfunctions"></xref>.
          Is the function <m>d</m> an injection?
          Is the function <m>d</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-9">
        <p>
          In <xref ref="PA_otherfunctions"></xref>
          from <xref ref="S_introfunctions"></xref>,
          we introduced the <em>birthday function</em>.
    <idx><h>birthday function</h></idx>
Is the birthday function an injection?
          Is it a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-10">
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f\x\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> be defined by <m>f( {m, n} ) = 2m + n</m>.
              Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
              Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
              Justify your conclusions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>g\x\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> be defined by <m>g( {m, n} ) = 6m + 3n</m>.
              Is the function <m>g</m> an injection?
              Is the function <m>g</m> a surjection?
              Justify your conclusions.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec63-11">
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>f\x\mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R} \times \mathbb{R}</m> be defined by <m>f( {x, y} ) = ( {2x, x + y} )</m>.
              Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
              Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
              Justify your conclusions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>g\x\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z}</m> be defined by <m>g( {x, y} ) = ( {2x, x + y} )</m>.
              Is the function <m>g</m> an injection?
              Is the function <m>g</m> a surjection?
              Justify your conclusions.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>f\x\R \times \R \to \R</m> be the function defined by <m>f (x, y ) = -x^2y+3y</m>,
          for all <m>(x, y ) \in \R \times \R</m>.
          Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
          Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>g\x\R \times \R \to \R</m> be the function defined by <m>g (x, y ) = ( x^3 + 2) \sin y</m>,
          for all <m>(x, y ) \in \R \times \R</m>.
          Is the function <m>g</m> an injection?
          Is the function <m>g</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a nonempty set.
          The <em>identity function on the set</em>
            <idx><h>identity function</h></idx>
          <m>\boldsymbol{A}</m>, denoted by <m>I_A</m>,
          is the function <m>I_A \x A \to A</m> defined by
          <m>I_A ( x ) = x</m> for every <m>x</m> in <m>A</m>.
          Is <m>I_A</m> an injection?
          Is <m>I_A</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let  <m>A</m>  and  <m>B</m>  be two nonempty sets.
          Define
          <me>
            p_1 \x A \times B \to A \text{ by }   p_1 ( {a, b} ) = a
          </me>
          for every  <m>( {a, b} ) \in A \times B</m>.
          This is the <em>first projection function</em>
            <idx><h>projection function</h></idx>
          introduced in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="sym_projfunc"/> in <xref ref="S_moreaboutfunctions"></xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the function <m>p_1</m> a surjection?
                Justify your conclusion.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>B = \left\{ b \right\}</m>,
                is the function <m>p_1</m> an injection?
                Justify your conclusion.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Under what condition(s) is the function <m>p_1</m> not an injection?
                Make a conjecture and prove it.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Define <m>f:\N \to \Z</m> as follows: For each <m>n \in \N</m>,
          <me>
            f(n) = \dfrac{1 + (-1)^n (2n - 1)}{4}
          </me>.
          Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
          Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
          <em>Suggestions</em>.
          Start by calculating several outputs for the function before you attempt to write a proof.
          In exploring whether or not the function is an injection,
          it might be a good idea to use cases based on whether the inputs are even or odd.
          In exploring whether <m>f</m> is a surjection,
          consider using cases based on whether the output is positive or less than or equal to zero.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>C</m> be the set of all real functions that are continuous on the closed interval <m>\left[ 0, 1 \right]</m>.
          Define the function <m>A\x C \to \mathbb{R}</m> as follows: For each <m>f \in C</m>,
          <me>
            A ( f ) = \int_0^1 {f( x ) \, dx}
          </me>.
          Is the function <m>A</m> an injection?
          Is it a surjection?
          Justify your conclusions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>A = \left\{ ( m, n ) \mid m \in \mathbb{Z}, n \in \mathbb{Z}, \text{ and } n \ne 0 \right\}</m>.
          Define <m>f\x A \to \mathbb{Q}</m> as follows:
          <ul>
            \item For each <m>( m, n ) \in A</m>, <m>f ( m, n ) = \dfrac{m+n}{n}</m>.
          </ul>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
                Justify your conclusion.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
                Justify your conclusion.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Evaluation of proofs</em>  See the instructions for Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_proofeval"/> on <xref ref="exer_proofeval">page</xref>
          from <xref ref="S_directproof"></xref>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <em>Proposition</em>.
                The function <m>f\x\R \times \R \to \R \times \R</m> defined by <m>f( {x, y} ) = ( {2x + y, x - y} )</m> is an injection.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    For each <m>(a, b)</m> and <m>(c, d)</m> in <m>\R \times \R</m>,
                    if <m>f(a, b) = f(c, d)</m>, then
                    <me>
                      (2a + b, a - b) = (2c + d, c - d)
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We will use systems of equations to prove that <m>a = c</m> and <m>b = d</m>.
                    <md>
                      <mrow>2a + b \amp = 2c + d</mrow>
                      <mrow>a - b \amp =  c - d</mrow>
                      <mrow>3a  \amp = 3c</mrow>
                      <mrow>a  \amp = c</mrow>
                    </md>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Since <m>a = c</m>, we see that
                    <me>
                      (2c + b, c - b) = (2c + d, c - d)
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    So <m>b = d</m>.
                    Therefore, we have proved that the function <m>f</m> is an injection.
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <em>Proposition</em>.
                The function <m>f\x\R \times \R \to \R \times \R</m> defined by <m>f( {x, y} ) = ( {2x + y, x - y} )</m> is a surjection.
                <proof>
                  <p>
                    We need to find an ordered pair such that
                    <m>f(x, y) = (a, b)</m> for each <m>(a, b)</m> in <m>\R \times \R</m>.
                    That is, we need <m>(2x + y, x - y) = (a, b)</m>, or
                    <me>
                      2x + y = a \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad x - y = b
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Treating these two equations as a system of equations and solving for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                    we find that
                    <me>
                      x = \frac{a + b}{3} \qquad \text{ and }  \qquad y = \frac{a - 2b}{3}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Hence, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are real numbers,
                    <m>(x, y) \in \R \times \R</m>, and
                    <md>
                      <mrow>f(x, y) \amp = f \left( \frac{a + b}{3}, \frac{a - 2b}{3} \right)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp = \left(2 \left( \frac{a + b}{3} \right) + \frac{a - 2b}{3}, \frac{a + b}{3} - \frac{a - 2b}{3} \right)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{2a + 2b + a - 2b}{3}, \frac{a + b - a + 2b}{3} \right)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{3a}{3}, \frac{3b}{3} \right)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp = (a, b)</mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Therefore, we have proved that for every <m>(a, b) \in \R \times \R</m>,
                    there exists an <m>(x, y) \in \R \times \R</m> such that <m>f(x, y) = (a, b)</m>.
                    This proves that the function <m>f</m> is a surjection.
                  </p>
                </proof>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Explorations and Activities</title>
    <ol>
      <li xml:id="exer_piecewisefunction">
        <p>
          <em>Piecewise Defined Functions</em>.
          We often say that a function is a
          <em>piecewise defined function</em>
    <idx><h>function</h><h>piecewise defined</h></idx>
    <idx><h>piecewise defined function</h></idx>
          if it has different rules for determining the output for different parts of its domain.
          For example, we can define a function
          <m>f\x\R \to \R</m> by giving a rule for calculating <m>f(x)</m> when
          <m>x \geq 0</m> and giving a rule for calculating <m>f(x)</m> when <m>x \lt  0</m> as follows:
          <men>
            f(x) = \begin{cases}x^2 + 1,    \amp   \text{ if \(x \geq 0\); }  \\ x - 1      \amp   \text{ if \(x \lt  0\). } \end{cases}
          </men>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Sketch a graph of the function <m>f</m>.
                Is the function <m>f</m> an injection?
                Is the function <m>f</m> a surjection?
                Justify your conclusions.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        For each of the following functions, determine if the function is an injection and determine if the function is a surjection.  Justify all conclusions.
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell>" <em>(b) </em> <m>g\x[0, 1] \to (0, 1)</m> by
              <men>
                g(x) = \begin{cases}0.8,      \amp   \text{ if \(x = 0\); }  \\ 0.5 x,    \amp   \text{ if \(0 \lt  x \lt  1\); }  \\ 0.6       \amp   \text{ if \(x = 1\). } \end{cases}
              </men>
              " <em>(c) </em> <m>h\x\Z \to \left\{ 0, 1 \right\}</m> by
              <men>
                h(x) = \begin{cases}0,        \amp  \text{ if \(x\) is even; }  \\ 1,        \amp  \text{ if \(x\) is odd. } \end{cases}
              </men>
              "</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Functions Whose Domain is <m>\boldsymbol{\mathcal{M}_2(\R)}</m></em>.
          Let  <m>\mathcal{M}_2 ( \R )</m> represent the set of all  2 by 2  matrices over  <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="sym_detfunc">
              <p>
                Define  <m>\det \x\mathcal{M}_2( \R ) \to \mathbb{R}</m> by
                <me>
                  \det \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} a \amp  b  \\ c \amp  d \end{array}  } \right] = ad - bc
                </me>.
                This is the <em>determinant function</em>
    <idx><h>determinant</h></idx>
                introduced in Exercise<nbsp/>(exer_determinant) from <xref ref="S_moreaboutfunctions"></xref>.
                Is the determinant function an injection?
                Is the determinant function a surjection?
                Justify your conclusions.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="sym_tranfunc">
              <p>
                Define <m>\text{ tran } \x\mathcal{M}_2( \R ) \to \mathcal{M}_2 ( \R )</m> by
                <me>
                  \text{ tran } \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} a \amp  b  \\ c \amp  d \end{array}  } \right] = A^T  = \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} a \amp  c  \\ b \amp  d \end{array}  } \right]
                </me>.
                This is the <em>transpose function</em>
    <idx><h>transpose</h></idx>
                introduced in Exercise<nbsp/>(exer_transpose) from <xref ref="S_moreaboutfunctions"></xref>.
                Is the transpose function an injection?
                Is the transpose function a surjection?
                Justify your conclusions.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="sym_detfunc">
              <p>
                Define <m>F \x\mathcal{M}_2( \R ) \to \mathbb{R}</m> by
                <me>
                  F \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} a \amp  b  \\ c \amp  d \end{array}  } \right] = a^2 + d^2 - b^2 - c^2
                </me>.
                Is the function <m>F</m> an injection?
                Is the function <m>F</m> a surjection?
                Justify your conclusions.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
